00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:46.810
And to avoid spoilers, I'm
going to read a little bit

00:00:46.810 --> 00:00:51.970
from Xanther's
father's perspective,

00:00:51.970 --> 00:00:55.010
and then-- actually, from
Xanther's mother's perspective,

00:00:55.010 --> 00:00:57.570
and then I will
read a little bit

00:00:57.570 --> 00:01:00.420
from her father's perspective.

00:01:00.420 --> 00:01:03.190
So Astair is up
in a place called

00:01:03.190 --> 00:01:09.140
Oceanica, where she is
training to be a therapist,

00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:10.250
and she's in a class.

00:01:14.950 --> 00:01:19.180
"'Is good thinking
terrifying?' Sandra D. Taylor,

00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:24.540
their doula of Oceanica, asks
a room of 70 on Saturday,

00:01:24.540 --> 00:01:26.060
August 9.

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:28.560
'Good thinking, I
like to think, is.

00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:31.740
And I like to think about
it a great deal, too.

00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:34.730
Though whether I manage any of
it is another story completely,

00:01:34.730 --> 00:01:38.420
contested perhaps too
frequently by my grandchildren,

00:01:38.420 --> 00:01:40.940
and gratefully by you.

00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:45.040
Good thinking, I like to
think, is hard thinking.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:50.680
And what makes hard thinking?'
Again, a genuine question.

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:52.680
'Consider this definition.

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:55.370
Hard thinking is
when we don't merely

00:01:55.370 --> 00:01:59.310
apply preexisting rationales
to routine patterns.

00:01:59.310 --> 00:02:01.450
For example, in the
way we might observe

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:05.940
events, note interactions,
evaluate emotional responses.

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:08.220
But instead acquire
a completely new set

00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:12.180
of values and parameters to
reencounter and reinterpret

00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:15.080
these common events,
interactions,

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:18.040
emotional responses.

00:02:18.040 --> 00:02:20.450
'That's then one model
for hard thinking.

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:26.090
Hard because acquiring a new
set of values is hard work.

00:02:26.090 --> 00:02:29.750
But is it terrifying?'
Astair has an answer,

00:02:29.750 --> 00:02:31.790
but not the confidence
to voice it.

00:02:31.790 --> 00:02:34.740
Her hangover isn't helping.

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:38.070
'Because our sense of
self, our identity--"

00:02:38.070 --> 00:02:41.200
Did Sandra D. Just stare
directly at Astair?

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:42.650
Even linger there?

00:02:42.650 --> 00:02:46.600
'Frequently find stabilization,
if not outright resolution,

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:49.910
in rationales inculcated
at an early age.

00:02:49.910 --> 00:02:51.410
Examples, please.'

00:02:51.410 --> 00:02:53.050
Hands shoot up,
though not Astair's,

00:02:53.050 --> 00:02:55.110
followed by a clatter of voices.

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:58.660
'Catholicism,' 'Mormonism,'
'Judaism,' 'Islam,' 'party

00:02:58.660 --> 00:03:01.830
affiliation,' 'sexual
orientation,' 'racial bias,'

00:03:01.830 --> 00:03:07.240
'scientific method,' 'trbal
ritual,' 'taboo.' 'Good.

00:03:07.240 --> 00:03:10.570
Religious rubrics, political
praxis, clan morals,

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:13.480
parental jurisprudence,
gender habits.

00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:17.860
A long list, as we can
all agree, incomplete.

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:20.570
Changing any of those
modes of engagement

00:03:20.570 --> 00:03:24.080
must necessitate a departure
from the original self, which

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:29.990
by the renegotiation can go so
far as to displace the self.

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:32.310
'And whether the
response is fatigue--

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:37.010
getting drowsy-- or boredom--
getting antsy-- or anger--

00:03:37.010 --> 00:03:42.420
getting just that-- that is
most certainly terrifying.

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:44.690
Though isn't the
alternative worse?

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:47.370
To live many lives in heaven.

00:03:47.370 --> 00:03:53.340
Hell is not to live even one.'

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:56.310
And that's just the beginning
Sandra D. Taylor speaks

00:03:56.310 --> 00:03:59.290
for another 90 minutes, though
today for some reason Astair

00:03:59.290 --> 00:04:00.910
stops taking notes.

00:04:00.910 --> 00:04:03.420
There is a difference between
work that is constructive

00:04:03.420 --> 00:04:05.570
and work that is compulsion.

00:04:05.570 --> 00:04:07.100
Note the difference.

00:04:07.100 --> 00:04:10.160
Beware the consequences
of not noting.

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:13.830
Working hard is not
the same as hard work.

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:17.370
Good work, good thinking,
even good living-- this

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:18.274
is what we pursue.

00:04:21.990 --> 00:04:24.390
Which Astair remembers
perfectly, she thinks.

00:04:24.390 --> 00:04:26.885
Even if her hand collapses
into some private,

00:04:26.885 --> 00:04:29.190
inkless fugue of heaviness.

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:32.010
Her lids also engage
in the same heaviness,

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:36.050
even as some kind of
internal lid begins to open.

00:04:36.050 --> 00:04:39.730
Somehow Sandra D.'s
talk demands it.

00:04:39.730 --> 00:04:43.740
She says things like, 'Life
would be so wonderful if we

00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:45.680
only knew what to do with it.

00:04:45.680 --> 00:04:47.110
But why wonder?

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:50.180
Remember, no choice is
rendered any less significant

00:04:50.180 --> 00:04:53.650
or impactful if made with
an even greater application

00:04:53.650 --> 00:04:57.460
of kindness.'

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:01.860
Or, 'Think before you act,
then act without thinking.' Or,

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:05.560
'To find yourself again, go find
yourself in this world where

00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:07.510
you are not of this world.

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:11.390
In other words, see new
places, meet new faces,

00:05:11.390 --> 00:05:15.100
travel.' That one earns
much laughter and applause,

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:17.790
as many of her remarks do.

00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:20.560
'Why keep escaping
from what makes us us?

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:28.430
As we are in a vocation
rooted in feelings,

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:31.250
let us not forget that
immaturity is frequently

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:34.610
reflected in the belief
that strong feelings ratify

00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:36.500
every action.

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:41.290
In other words, and to be
prescriptive, let us be mature.

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:45.480
Remember, you future counselors
and bringers of relief,

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:48.270
there will never be a
cure for life's problems,

00:05:48.270 --> 00:05:52.430
because so many of tomorrow's
problems will be new.

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:55.240
Good words like good
work and good thinking

00:05:55.240 --> 00:06:00.330
help, even if good words are
a lot like highway paint--

00:06:00.330 --> 00:06:02.400
they can keep plenty
of heavy things moving

00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:06.450
at 70 miles per hour
from going the wrong way,

00:06:06.450 --> 00:06:10.020
but that doesn't mean life
won't cross over if it has to.

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:15.050
Learn to avoid the collisions.'

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:16.630
'Find other directions.

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:20.060
Often a new yes is the best no.

00:06:20.060 --> 00:06:23.370
Life lived well doesn't get
easier, but it does get better.

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:38.800
Learn to let things go by,
and don't be reluctant.

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:41.200
Life is always surpassing us by.

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:50.110
Enjoy it.'"

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:54.160
This is from
Anwar's perspective.

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:58.340
They are at a baseball game.

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:02.870
"Far below, a dodger,
number 10, swings his bat.

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:06.760
Even up here, the sound of
that wallop reaches them.

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:09.750
Anwar and Xanther rise
together with the whole stadium

00:07:09.750 --> 00:07:12.150
it seems-- their
sections, at least.

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:13.170
Everyone's cheering.

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:17.940
Xanther and Anwar
sure are cheering.

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:19.400
It feels good.

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:24.250
The ball flies deep
into left field,

00:07:24.250 --> 00:07:27.790
and with the peculiar magic of
a home run, seems to keep going,

00:07:27.790 --> 00:07:30.070
during the night sky.

00:07:30.070 --> 00:07:33.410
Xanther jumps up and down,
excitedly waving her Dodgers

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:37.470
hat, up on her seat, until
she jumps into Anwar's arms

00:07:37.470 --> 00:07:40.282
with such big, excited hug.

00:07:40.282 --> 00:07:43.880
And Anwar, lifting Xanther
up, holding her tight,

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:45.900
is suddenly missing his mother.

00:07:45.900 --> 00:07:49.420
Out of nowhere, terribly,
she comes upon him

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:51.340
with all she ever
was-- her smile,

00:07:51.340 --> 00:07:53.530
her kindness, her goodness.

00:07:53.530 --> 00:07:56.640
How Anwar would have loved
to have seen Fatima here,

00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:58.130
now with Xanther.

00:07:58.130 --> 00:08:00.540
Would they have hugged too?

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:02.920
What would they have
said to each other later?

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:05.350
How would they have
teased and laughed

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:09.010
and sparred, together wondered?

00:08:09.010 --> 00:08:11.920
Do we miss not only the
past, but every feature

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:15.210
the lost past describes?

00:08:15.210 --> 00:08:18.070
Is that just the nature
of missing, all the lost

00:08:18.070 --> 00:08:19.830
might-have-beens?

00:08:19.830 --> 00:08:25.070
The certainty that those
uncertain futures are gone.

00:08:25.070 --> 00:08:29.620
If we can't embrace uncertainty,
do we miss the point of love?

00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:31.390
Thank you.

